# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-kentucky-gubernatorial-election] The **1792 Kentucky gubernatorial election** was held on May 17, 1791, in order to elect the first Governor of Kentucky upon Kentucky acquiring statehood on June 1, 1792.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-kentucky-gubernatorial-election] Democratic-Republican nominee Isaac Shelby was elected unanimously by an electoral college vote.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-kentucky-gubernatorial-election] Until 1800, Kentucky elected its governors through electors who were chosen via popular vote from the same districts as the Kentucky House of Representatives.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-kentucky-gubernatorial-election] On election day, May 17, 1791, Democratic-Republican nominee Isaac Shelby won the election after being unanimously chosen by an electoral college vote, thereby gaining Democratic-Republican control over the office of Governor.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-kentucky-gubernatorial-election] Shelby was sworn in as the 1st Governor of Kentucky on June 4, 1792.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-kentucky] A presidential election was held in Kentucky between November 2 and December 5, 1792, as part of the 1792 United States presidential election.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-kentucky] The voters chose four representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for President and Vice President.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-kentucky] It was the first presidential election Kentucky participated in since being admitted to the Union on June 1, 1792.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-kentucky] Kentucky cast four electoral votes for the Independent candidate and incumbent President George Washington, as he ran effectively unopposed.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-kentucky] The electoral votes for Vice president were cast for Democratic-Republican Thomas Jefferson from Virginia, the only state to do so.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-kentucky] The state was divided into four electoral districts with one elector each, whereupon each district's voters chose the electors.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] The **1792–93 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states, coinciding with President George Washington's unanimous re-election.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] Senate elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1792 and 1793, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] In these elections, terms were up for the ten senators in Class 2.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] Formal organized political parties had yet to form in the United States, but two political factions were present: The coalition of Senators who supported George Washington's administration were known as the Pro-Administration Party, and the Senators against him as the Anti-Administration Party.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] Virginia's elections are considered a single race here.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] After the June 1792 admission of Kentucky.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] Two Pro-Administration senators (Benjamin Hawkins of North Carolina and John Langdon of New Hampshire) changed to Anti-Administration.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] The vacant seat in Pennsylvania was filled February 28, 1793 by an Anti-Administration senator.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] In these elections, the winner was seated before March 4, 1793; ordered by election date.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] In these regular elections, the winner was seated on March 4, 1793; ordered by state.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] All of the elections involved the Class 2 seats.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] In this special election, the winner was seated after March 4, 1793, the beginning of the next Congress.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] One-term Anti-Federalist William Few was defeated by fellow Anti-Federalist, James Jackson.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] Jackson won 24 votes in the Georgia House of Representatives and 11 in the State Senate for a combined total of 35.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] Few won 3 in the House and 2 in the Senate for a combined total of 5.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] Jackson took office as a member of the 3rd United States Congress on March 4, 1793.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] He would later resign in 1795 to run for his state's legislature.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] Incumbent John Brown, who had previously been elected in a special election was easily reelected with no opposition and 100% of votes from the legislators.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] Richard Potts won election to fill the seat vacated by Charles Carroll over Josh Hoskins Stone by a margin of 21.84%, or 19 votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] Senator Paine Wingate was not reelected.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] The New Hampshire General Court instead elected Federalist Samuel Livermore, a U.S.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] Livermore, like his fellow senator, John Langdon, would go on to serve as President Pro-Tempore during this term.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] Pro-Administration Samuel Johnston lost re-election to Anti-Administration Alexander Martin for the class 2 seat.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] The other senator, Benjamin Hawkins, switched his support from Pro- to Anti-Administration.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] There was a special election on February 28, 1793, for the Class 1 seat from Pennsylvania.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] Incumbent William Maclay's term had ended on March 3, 1791, but the legislature failed to elect a successor due to a disagreement on the procedure to be followed in the election.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] The seat remained vacant until Albert Gallatin was elected by the Pennsylvania General Assembly to the seat during this election.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] Upon agreement between the two houses of the Pennsylvania General Assembly, the House of Representatives and the Senate, regarding the procedure to elect a new Senator, an election was finally held on February 28, 1793.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] On February 28, 1794, the Senate determined that Gallatin did not satisfy the citizenship requirement for service and he was removed from office.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] Gallatin was replaced in the Senate by a special election in 1794.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] Anti-Administration senator Richard Henry Lee resigned October 8, 1792, just before the March 3, 1793 end of term.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1792-united-states-senate-elections-in-kentucky] Anti-administration John Taylor of Caroline was elected October 18, 1792 to finish Lee's term and then re-elected in 1793 to the next term.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] The **1792–93 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between August 27, 1792, and September 6, 1793.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 3rd United States Congress convened on December 2, 1793.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] With the addition of the new state of Kentucky's representatives, and the congressional reapportionment based on the 1790 United States census, the size of the House increased to 105 seats.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] They coincided with the re-election of President George Washington.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] While Washington ran for president as an independent, his followers (more specifically, the supporters of Alexander Hamilton) formed the nation's first organized political party, the Federalist Party, whose members and sympathizers are identified as pro-Administration on this page.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] In response, followers of Thomas Jefferson and James Madison created the opposition Democratic-Republican Party, who are identified as anti-Administration on this page.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] The Federalists promoted urbanization, industrialization, mercantilism, a centralized government, and a broad interpretation of the United States Constitution.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] In contrast, the Democratic-Republicans supported the ideal of an agrarian republic made up of self-sufficient farmers and small, localized governments with limited power.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Despite nearly unanimous support for Washington as a presidential candidate, Jeffersonian ideas edged out Hamiltonian principles at the ballot box for congressional candidates, with the Democratic-Republicans taking 24 seats more than they had prior to the organization of their political movement.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Most of the increase was due to the addition of new seats in Western regions as a result of the 1790 census.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Dominated by agrarian culture, these Western territories offered strong support to Democratic-Republican congressional candidates.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] As a result, they secured a thin majority in the legislature.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] In this period, each state fixed its own date for its congressional election as early as August 1792 (in New Hampshire and Rhode Island) and as late as September 1793 (in Kentucky).
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year), but as the first session of Congress typically began in November or December, the elections took place before Congress actually met.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] The 3rd Congress first met on December 2, 1793.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] These were the first elections held after reapportionment following the first census.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Thirty-six new seats were added, with 1 state losing 1 seat, 3 states having no change, and the remaining 11 states gaining between 1 and 9 seats.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] This was the first apportionment based on actual census data, the apportionment for the 1st and 2nd Congresses being set by the Constitution using estimated populations.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] With new seats, due to reapportionment, outlined.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] There were special elections in 1792 and 1793 during the 2nd and 3rd United States Congresses.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Elections are sorted here by state then district.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Connecticut gained two seats in reapportionment following the 1790 census.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Three special elections followed the 1792 elections in Connecticut after Representatives-elect Sturges and Huntington resigned before the start of Congress and Mitchell was elected to the Senate.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Delaware's apportionment did not change following the 1790 census.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] As in the 1st and 2nd Congresses, each voter cast votes for two separate candidates, at least one of whom had to be from a different county as the voter.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Following the 1790 census, Georgia's apportionment was decreased from 3 seats to 2 (the only state whose representation decreased after the census).
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Georgia switched from separate districts to at-large seats.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Maryland increased from 6 to 8 representatives after the 1790 census.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] The previous mixed district/at-large system was replaced with a conventional district system.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Following the 1790 census, Massachusetts's representation increased from eight to fourteen Representatives and was redistricted into four plural districts, plus a single at-large district.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] The 4th district covered the District of Maine (the modern-day State of Maine).
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] The plural districts were concurrent tickets rather than a single general ticket, though the 1st and 2nd districts appeared to have also had a general ticket alongside the more specific tickets.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] As before, a majority was required for election, in those districts where a majority was not achieved, additional ballots were required.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] New Hampshire increased from 3 seats to 4 seats after the 1790 census.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Following the 1790 census, New Jersey's apportionment increased from 4 to 5 seats.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, New York's congressional delegation grew from 6 to 10.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Three incumbents ran for re-election, two of whom won, and the other three incumbents retired.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] With the increase following re-apportionment, this left seven open seats.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Following the 1790 census, North Carolina's apportionment increased from 5 to 10 seats.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Pennsylvania switched from using districts to electing its representatives on an at-large basis for the 3rd Congress, just as it had done for the 1st Congress.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] This would be the last time that Pennsylvania would elect all of its Representatives at-large.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, Pennsylvania's delegation increased from 8 representatives to 13.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Rhode Island gained a second representative from the results of the 1790 census.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Rhode Island did not divide itself into districts, but elected two at-large representatives.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] South Carolina gained one representative as a result of the 1790 census, increasing from 5 to 6.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Vermont had no apportionment in the House of Representatives before 1790 census because it was not admitted to the Union until 1791.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Vermont's election laws at the time required a majority to win election to the House of Representatives.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] If no candidate won a majority, a runoff election was held, which happened in the 1st district.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] Virginia gained nine representatives from the 1790 census, and in addition, the old 2nd district was lost after its territory became the new State of Kentucky.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-kentucky] There were, therefore, ten new districts created for the 3rd Congress.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] The **1794–95 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1794 and 1795, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] In these elections, terms were up for the senators in Class 3.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] This was the first election cycle with organized political parties in the United States, with the Federalist Party emerging from the Pro Administration coalition, and the Democratic-Republican Party emerging from the Anti-Administration coalition.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] After the March 31, 1794 special election in Pennsylvania.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] Seven senators who were considered "Anti-Administration" became Democratic-Republicans and eleven "Pro-Administration" became Federalists.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] Except if/when noted, the number following candidates is the whole number vote(s), not a percentage.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] In these special elections, the winner was seated before March 4, 1795; ordered by election date.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] In these regular elections, the winner was seated on March 4, 1795; ordered by state.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] All of the elections involved the Class 3 seats.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] There were no elections in 1795 after March 4.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] The **Delaware special election** was held February 7, 1795.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] Incumbent Senator George Read had resigned to take the position of Chief Justice of the Delaware Supreme Court.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] Henry Latimer defeated the former Governor of Delaware, Governor of Pennsylvania and Continental Congressmen from Delaware and Pennsylvania by one vote.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] John Henry won election over James Lloyd by an unknown number of votes for the Class 3 seat.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] Incumbent Federalist Robert Morris, who was elected in 1788, was not a candidate for re-election to another term.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] The Pennsylvania General Assembly convened on February 26, 1795, to elect a senator for the term beginning March 4, 1795.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] Even though neither of Virginia's incumbent's terms were up, both resigned in 1794, leading to two special elections.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] Future-president James Monroe resigned March 27, 1794 to become U.S.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] Stevens Thomson Mason was elected November 18, 1794 and would become a Democratic-Republican in the next Congress.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] Incumbent John Taylor of Caroline resigned May 11, 1794.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-kentucky] Henry Tazewell was elected November 18, 1794 and would become a Democratic-Republican in the next Congress.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election] The **1808 Kentucky gubernatorial election** was held on August 1, 1808, in order to elect the Governor of Kentucky.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election] Democratic-Republican candidate Charles Scott defeated fellow Democratic-Republican candidates John Allen and Green Clay.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election] On election day, August 1, 1808, Democratic-Republican candidate Charles Scott won the election by a margin of 13,620 votes against his foremost opponent fellow Democratic-Republican candidate John Allen, thereby retaining Democratic-Republican control over the office of governor.
[src:1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election/1808-kentucky-gubernatorial-election] Scott was sworn in as the 4th governor of Kentucky on August 23, 1808.
